# Scoped, Verifiable Changes

These rules apply to every agent request in this project. Bias toward caution over speed unless the task is trivial.

## Think Before Coding

- State assumptions when the request is ambiguous. If multiple interpretations exist, ask or present the tradeoff instead of silently choosing.
- If a simpler approach exists, say so. Push back when the requested path would add avoidable risk.
- When confused, stop and name what is unclear before editing.

## Simplicity First

- Write the minimum code that solves the requested behavior.
- Do not add speculative features, generic abstractions, configurability, or impossible-scenario handling.
- If a solution is getting large, simplify before continuing.

## Surgical Changes

- Before editing, identify the exact behavior the user asked to change and the files that own it.
- Keep changes limited to that behavior. Do not refactor, restyle, rename, reformat, or broaden logic unless required.
- Match existing style, even if a different style looks cleaner.
- Do not improve adjacent code, comments, or formatting as a side effect.
- Remove only imports, variables, or code made unused by your own change.
- Mention unrelated dead code or dirty files instead of deleting or staging them.
- Every changed line should trace directly to the user's request.

## Goal-Driven Execution

- For bug fixes, reproduce or inspect the failing path first, then change the smallest surface that explains it.
- Define success criteria before implementation on multi-step work.
- Preserve working behavior around the change. If shared code is touched, check nearby call sites and add or update focused tests.
- Prefer small, reversible patches. Avoid coupling unrelated fixes into the same edit or commit.
- Before committing, review the diff and remove accidental churn.
